{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15156"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15156"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.16,0.29,0.09,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84742"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69031"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3639"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35732"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84742"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-day history of fever, headache, widespread pruritic rash, conjunctivitis, and joint pain. He returned from a two-week holiday in Philippines eight days ago. He has a history of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and takes omeprazole as needed. He reports unprotected sexual intercourse with multiple partners while travelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.3\u00b0C. He has a morbilliform rash over his trunk and limbs including his palms and soles, bilateral non-purulent conjunctival injection, and dry mucous membranes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rapid Plasma Reagin","Chikungunya virus PCR","Zika virus PCR","Urine culture","Dengue IgM antibodies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms of Zika virus infection including fever, rash, conjunctivitis, and arthralgia following travel to an endemic area. The timing of presentation (six days after symptom onset) is crucial in determining the most appropriate diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZika virus PCR\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate test within seven days of symptom onset. Both serum and urine samples should be collected, as viral RNA can be detected in urine for up to 14 days after symptom onset. After this period, serological testing becomes more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid Plasma Reagin\u003C/strong\u003E testing would be inappropriate as the first-line test. While syphilis can cause fever and rash, the acute onset, travel history, and constellation of symptoms are more suggestive of an arboviral infection. The morbilliform rash is more typical of Zika virus, whereas syphilis usually presents with a non-pruritic maculopapular rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChikungunya virus PCR\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as part of the workup as it can cause similar symptoms and is transmitted by the same vector. However, given the clinical presentation and travel history, Zika virus testing should be prioritised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine culture\u003C/strong\u003E would not be appropriate as there are no urinary symptoms, and this would not help diagnose a mosquito-borne viral infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue IgM antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E testing would not be the most appropriate initial test, although dengue is in the differential diagnosis. Dengue typically presents with high fever rather than low-grade fever, and the rash is usually not pruritic. Additionally, serological testing this early may yield false-negative results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Real-time PCR testing of serum and urine is the preferred diagnostic test for Zika virus infection within 7 days of symptom onset.","Zika virus infection typically presents with fever, pruritic rash, non-purulent conjunctivitis, and arthralgia.","Travel history and timing of symptom onset are crucial factors in determining appropriate testing strategy for arboviral infections."],"references":["Cordel N, Birembaux X, Chaumont H, et al. Main Characteristics of Zika Virus Exanthema in Guadeloupe. JAMA Dermatol. 2017;153(4):326\u2013328. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamadermatology/fullarticle/2604250#google_vignette","Oakley A. Zika Virus. In: DermNet NZ [online]. 2016. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/zika-virus"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69031"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15156"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69031"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T15:45:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T15:48:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"